{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502535","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502535"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:45:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:45:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1869"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1869","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1869"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.23,0.08,0.1,0.43]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1869"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106989"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1869","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1869"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1869"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89453"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3365"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4377"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10816"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16179"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38183"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43858"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106989","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106989"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 51-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for review after an abnormal liver function pattern on routine testing. He has otherwise been well. He has a medical history of hypertension, hyperlipidaemia, and type 2 diabetes. His regular medications include ramipril and metformin. He is a non-smoker and drinks no more than two glasses of wine at weekends, and his consumption has never been greater than this. He denies recreational drug use and has not previously travelled overseas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His physical examination is unremarkable, apart from a BMI of 36 kg/m2. Investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAlbumin 34 g/L (34-48)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EGlobulin 36 g/L (21-41)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAlkaline phosphatase 35 U/L (30-110)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EGamma-glutamyl transferase 40 U/L (0-59)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAspartate aminotransferase 81 U/L (0-44)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAlanine aminotransferase 122 U/L (0-54)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation to establish the underlying diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hepatitis serology","Fibroscan","Liver biopsy","CT abdomen","Ultrasound"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s clinical picture is most consistent with metabolic dysfunction-associated fatty liver disease (MAFLD), formerly known as non-alcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD). This condition is an increasing health concern, with prevalence rising along with obesity and type 2 diabetes, such that it is now the most common cause of liver disease globally. The diagnosis of MAFLD is based on three factors: evidence of hepatic steatosis (by imaging or histology), exclusion of significant alcohol consumption, and exclusion of other causes of liver disease. This patient\u0027s clinical presentation (obesity, type 2 diabetes, hypertension, hyperlipidaemia) and liver function tests (elevated ALT and AST with an ALT:AST ratio \u0026gt;1.5) are highly suggestive of MAFLD. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first-line investigation to establish the diagnosis of MAFLD. It can provide confirmation of hepatic fatty infiltrate with high specificity and identify signs of cirrhosis. Ultrasound is non-invasive, widely available, and cost-effective, making it the preferred initial imaging modality for suspected MAFLD.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis serology\u003C/strong\u003E would be used to investigate viral hepatitis. While viral hepatitis can also cause deranged liver function tests with abnormal ALT and AST levels, this patient lacks risk factors for viral hepatitis, making it less likely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFibroscan\u003C/strong\u003E (transient elastography) is a non-invasive tool used to estimate the degree of liver fibrosis. While useful in staging MAFLD, it is not typically used as the initial diagnostic test. Fibroscan would be more appropriate after the diagnosis of MAFLD has been established to assess the severity of liver disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELiver biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is considered the gold standard for diagnosing and staging MAFLD. However, due to its invasive nature and associated risks, it is not used as a first-line investigation. Liver biopsy is typically reserved for cases where there is diagnostic uncertainty or concern for significant fibrosis or cirrhosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT abdomen\u003C/strong\u003E does not provide a definitive diagnosis for MAFLD and is not the preferred imaging modality for this condition. While CT can detect fatty liver, it is less sensitive than ultrasound and exposes the patient to radiation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFollowing diagnosis, it is important to stage the disease and monitor progression. This typically involves regular follow-up with repeat liver function tests every 6 months, as well as monitoring of other metabolic parameters such as lipid profile and blood pressure. Management focuses on lifestyle modifications, particularly weight loss through diet and exercise, which can lead to improvement in liver histology and function.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Metabolic dysfunction-associated fatty liver disease (MAFLD) is strongly associated with metabolic syndrome, including obesity, type 2 diabetes, hypertension, and dyslipidaemia.","Ultrasound is the first-line imaging modality for diagnosing MAFLD , providing confirmation of hepatic fatty infiltrate with high specificity."],"references":["MAFLD Consensus Statement Working Group. Recommendations for the assessment of metabolic dysfunction-associated fatty liver disease (MAFLD) in primary care: a consensus statement. Melbourne: Gastroenterological Society of Australia, 2024. Available at: https://www.gesa.org.au/public/13/files/Education%20%26%20Resources/Clinical%20Practice%20Resources/MAFLD/MAFLD%20consensus%20statement%202024.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89453"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1869"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89453","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89453"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-24T16:15:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-24T16:16:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1869"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106989"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms